          # PERFECT ANSWER (For An InterView)
In flutter, the widget lifecycle refers to the sequence of events that occurs from the moment
a widget is created until it is destroyed. However, a critical point to understand is that 
widgets themeselves are immutable - they are just configuration.
the actual lifecycle belongs to the state object attached to a stateful widget.
let me explain both scenario.

           1. Stateless Widget lifecycle:(very simple)
           -------------------------------------------
Stateless Widget has almost no lifecycle - they are build once and never changes.
     Constructor   ->    build    ->   Disposed (when removed from tree). 
         | called          |             |(no Clean up needed)
         |-------------------------------------> Widget is instantiated.
                           |-------------------> Called Once(unless parent rebuilds).
                                         |-----> Because no mutable state
Stateless widget can not rebuild themeselves - only there parent can replace them. 

           2. Stateful Widget lifecycle:(very simple)
           -------------------------------------------
This is what most interviewers mean when asking about widget lifecycle.
   Complete Flow Diagram (Mental Model):
StatefulWidget Constructor -> createState() -> State Constructor -> 
mounted = true <- safe to use set state after this  ->
initState() <- called once (initialize data, controllers).  ->
didChangeDependencies() <- called after initState() & when Inherited widget changes.  ->
build() <- called many times (UI rendering).   ->
setState() <- User triggers <- schedulers rebuild <- calls build() again.  ->
didUpdateWidget <- Called when parent rebuild with new widget config.
deactive <-  state removed from tree temporarily (e.g., during navigation).
dispose <- Called once (permanent cleanup).
mounted = false <- cannot called set state after this.

              REAL WORLD EXAMPLE IN FLUTTER: 
              ------------------------------
class MyWidget extends StatefulWidget {
 final String title;
 const MyWidget({ Key? key, required this.title}): super(key: key);
 @override
 State<MyWidget> createState() => _MyWidgetState();
}

class _MyWidgetState extends State<MyWidget>{
 late TextEditingController _controller;
 int _counter = 0;

 // 1. First method called after state is created
 @override
 void initState(){
  super.initState();
  _controller = TextEditingController();
  print("initState called - Initialize resources");
  // Never call setState() here.
 }

 // 2. Called after initState and when InheritedWidget changes.
 @override
 void didChangeDependencies(){
  super.didChangeDependencies();
  print("didChangeDependencies - Dependencies changed");
  // Safe to call setState() here if needed.
 }

 // 3. Called many times - builds the UI.
 @override
 Widget build(BuildContext context){
  print("build called - counter = $_counter");
  return Column(
   children: [
    Text(widget.title),  // Accessing Widget property
    Text("Counter: $_counter"),
    ElevatedButton(
     onPressed: (){
      setState((){
        _counter++;
      });
     },
     child: Text("Increment"),
    ),
   ],
  );
 }

 // 4. Called when parent widget build with new configuration.
 @override
 void didUpdateWidget(MyWidget oldwidget){
  super.didUpdateWidget(oldWidget);
  print('didUpdateWidget - title changed from ${oldwidget.title} to ${newwidget.title}');
  if(oldWidget.title != widget.title){
   // React to property changed
  }
 }

 // 5. Called when State is temporaryily removed
 @override
 void deactivate(){
  super.deactivate();
  print('deactive - State removed from tree');
 }

 // 6. Called Once before permanent destruction
 @override
 void dispose(){
  print("dispose - cleanup resources");
  _controller.dispose();  // CRICTICAL: Always dispose controllers
  super.dispose();
 }
}

                  COMMON INTERVIEW FOLLOW UP QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
                  -------------------------------------------------
Q) "How many times is 'build' called?"
As many times as needed - every time 'setState()' called, every time an InheritedWidget
changes, or when the parent widget rebuilds.

Q) "What happens if i call 'setState' in 'dispose'"?
It will throw an error because 'mounted' becomes 'false'. Always check if (mounted)
before calling 'setState'in async operations.

Q) "Difference between 'didChangeDependencies' and 'initState'"?
initState called once. 'didChangeDependencies' is called after 'initState' AND every time
an inheritedWidget (like 'Theme' or 'Provider') changes - useful for expensive operations
that depend on context.

Q) When should i use 'deactivate()'?
Rarely - mostly when the state is being moved from one part of the tree to another.
For 99% of cases, use 'dispose()' for cleanup.

              PERFECT ONE LINER SUMMARY(FOR QUICK ANSWER)
the widget lifecycle in flutter is managed by the State object of the StatefulWidget
- starting with 'initState', going through multiple 'build' calls triggered by 'setState'
and ending with 'dispose' to cleanup.
